-- Befimmo, Merck, Puma, Societe Generale, Total: European Equity Preview
-- Whitney Kisling
-- 2010-06-29T22:06:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-29/befimmo-merck-puma-societe-generale-total-european-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  lost 3 percent to 243.82. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  declined 3.1 percent to 2,356.81. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, slid 4.2
percent to 2,556.34.  
 Befimmo SCA  (BEFB BB): Belgium’s second-biggest real-estate
investment fund received a 51 million-euro ($62 million) offer
from Vivaqua for its Empress Court office in Brussels and
expects to record a gain of about 70 cents a share should an
agreement lead to a transaction. Befimmo declined 2.9 percent to
55.86 euros.  
 Merck KGaA  (MRK GY): Elmar Schnee, head of the company’s
pharmaceutical operations, expects an operating margin at its
Serono unit of as much as 25 percent, Platow Brief reported,
without saying where it got the information. The drugmaker is
confident its filing for cladribine, an experimental multiple
sclerosis pill, will be accepted by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, the newsletter said. The shares dropped 2.1
percent to 60.36 euros.  
 Puma AG  (PUM GY): The second-largest European sporting-
goods maker said it will receive all trademark rights in Spain
and will take over the operational business in the country.  
 The former Spanish license holder, Estudio 2000 SA, will
have to vest the rights after an arbitration ruling, Puma said.
The vesting is subject to a payment of as much as 98 million
euros ($119 million), which Puma will oppose. The shares sank
4.1 percent to 221.30 euros.  
 Sacyr Vallehermoso SA  (SYV SM): The builder will hold its
annual shareholders’ meeting. The shares fell 9.2 percent to
4.24 euros.  
 Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP): The bank cut its company bond
supply forecast for 2010 to 110 billion euros from a March
estimate of 140 billion euros, according to  Suki Mann , head of
credit strategy at SocGen in London. The shares fell 6.5 percent
to 33.80 euros.  
 Siemens AG  (SIE GY): Europe’s largest engineering company
plans to take a 49% stake in the offshore-wind installation unit
of Danish utility Dong Energy A/S for about 860 million kroner
($141 million). The shares fell 3.9 percent to 73.55 euros.  
 Total SA  (FP FP) and  Electricite de France  (EDF FP): The
two companies agreed to take a final decision on developing a
liquefied natural gas terminal at Dunkirk in northern France by
the end of 2010, Industry Minister Christian Estrosi said. Total
shares declined 3.6 percent to 36.76 euros, while EDF fell 2.9
percent to 31.35 euros.  
